use absent from the document)"},"explanation":"EDPB Recommendations 01/2020 require the parties to assess local laws and practices of the recipient country.","id":"TRANSFER-019-s1-0","recommendation":"Reference a TIA / TRA in the DPA / SCC Annex and document the supplementary measures where needed.","rule_id":"TRANSFER-019","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"critical","source_citations":[{"id":"transfer-edpb-recommendations-01-2020-on-supplementary-measures","license":"Public domain or regulator re-use","license_url":"https://www.usa.gov/government-works","retrieved_at":"2026-05-12T00:00:00Z","source":"EDPB Recommendations 01/2020 on Supplementary Measures","source_url":"https://edpb.europa.eu/our-work-tools/our-documents/recommendations/recommendations-012020-measures-supplement-transfer_en"}],"title":"TIA / Transfer Risk Assessment reference missing"},{"description":"The contract does not allocate ownership of intellectual property.","document_position":0,"excerpt":{"end_offset":0,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":0,"text":"(no IP-ownership clause)"},"explanation":"Without an IP-ownership clause, default copyright and patent rules apply: under 17 U.S.C. § 201, copyright vests in the author/employee unless work-for-hire or assignment applies.","id":"IPDATA-001-s1-0","rule_id":"IPDATA-001","rule_version":"1.1.0","severity":"warning","source_citations":[{"id":"stat-17-usc-101","license":"Public domain (US government work)","license_url":"https://www.usa.gov/government-works","retrieved_at":"2026-05-11T00:00:00Z","source":"17 U.S.C. § 101 — Definitions (work made for hire)","source_url":"https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/17/101"},{"id":"stat-17-usc-201","license":"Public domain (US government work)","license_url":"https://www.usa.gov/government-works","retrieved_at":"2026-05-11T00:00:00Z","source":"17 U.S.C. § 201","source_url":"https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/17/201"}],"title":"No IP-ownership clause detected"},{"description":"The contract references data handling (`personal data`) but no clause specifies retention duration or deletion obligations.","document_position":516,"excerpt":{"end_offset":529,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":516,"text":"personal data"},"explanation":"Under GDPR Article 5(1)(e), CCPA, and most modern data-protection regimes, the duration for which data is retained must be defined or tied to a defined purpose. A contract that handles data but says nothing about retention leaves the data subject without a contractual ceiling on how long their information can be held — and leaves the data controller without a clear obligation to delete.","id":"IPDATA-007-s1-516","recommendation":"Add an explicit retention clause: how long data is kept (or the trigger that ends retention), what happens at the end of retention (return / deletion / certification of destruction), and the cooperation timeline.","rule_id":"IPDATA-007","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"warning","source_citations":[],"title":"Data retention period unspecified"},{"description":"Neither 'indemnify' nor 'hold harmless' appears in the document.","document_position":0,"excerpt":{"end_offset":0,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":0,"text":"(no indemnification language)"},"explanation":"Most commercial contracts allocate risk through an indemnification clause. The absence leaves the parties to default tort and contract law for any third-party claims.","id":"RISK-001-s1-0","rule_id":"RISK-001","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"warning","source_citations":[],"title":"No indemnification clause detected"},{"description":"Vaulytica did not find a limitation-of-liability clause.","document_position":0,"excerpt":{"end_offset":0,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":0,"text":"(no LoL clause)"},"explanation":"Without a limitation-of-liability clause, exposure is bounded only by what the parties can prove in damages. Most commercial contracts cap liability.","id":"RISK-005-s1-0","rule_id":"RISK-005","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"warning","source_citations":[],"title":"No limitation-of-liability clause detected"},{"description":"No Effective Date is named, defined, or stated near the top of this Agreement.","document_position":0,"excerpt":{"end_offset":0,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":0,"text":"(no Effective Date reference matched)"},"explanation":"Most contracts identify a starting point that other date references rely on. Without it, relative terms like 'within 30 days after the Effective Date' have no anchor.","id":"STRUCT-002-s1-0","recommendation":"Add an Effective Date — either in the preamble ('dated as of [date]'), as a defined term, or as an explicit 'Effective Date: [date]' line.","rule_id":"STRUCT-002","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"warning","source_citations":[],"title":"No Effective Date found"},{"description":"Used but not defined: Approved Addendum, Data Protection Act, Mandatory Clauses, Restricted Transfers, Standard Contractual Clauses.","document_position":2023,"excerpt":{"end_offset":2040,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":2023,"text":"Approved Addendum"},"explanation":"Title-Case phrases in a contract usually signal a defined term. When they aren't defined, readers must guess at the intended meaning. Either define them or use lowercase if the term is intended in its ordinary sense.","id":"STRUCT-006-s1-2023","recommendation":"Add a definition for each genuinely defined term, or change the casing if the phrase is being used in its ordinary sense.","rule_id":"STRUCT-006","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"warning","source_citations":[],"title":"Undefined Title-Case terms: 5"},{"description":"The following references do not resolve to any section: Section 19, section 18.","document_position":2101,"excerpt":{"end_offset":2111,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":2101,"text":"Section 19"},"explanation":"A broken cross-reference can mean the referenced section was renumbered or deleted, or that a section reference was made up. Either way the reader has no way to follow the citation.","id":"STRUCT-007-s1-2101","recommendation":"Update each broken reference to point to the correct section, or delete it if it is no longer applicable.","rule_id":"STRUCT-007","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"warning","source_citations":[],"title":"Unresolved cross-references: 2"},{"description":"Addendum B is referenced but not attached to the document.","document_position":2260,"excerpt":{"end_offset":2270,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":2260,"text":"Addendum B"},"explanation":"The agreement refers to an exhibit, schedule, annex, appendix, or attachment that is not present in the document. If the referenced material carries operative terms, those terms are missing from the contract. (In folder mode, a referenced attachment that is a sibling file is reconciled before this is reported.) This is an internal-consistency check, not an assertion that the attachment is legally required.","id":"STRUCT-018-s1-2260","recommendation":"Attach each referenced item (Addendum B) before execution, or remove the reference if it is no longer needed. Reconcile every cross-reference to a present attachment as part of the closing checklist.","rule_id":"STRUCT-018","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"warning","source_citations":[],"title":"Referenced attachment not present: 1"},{"description":"The contract does not state a path to terminate for material breach.","document_position":0,"excerpt":{"end_offset":0,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":0,"text":"(no for-cause termination)"},"explanation":"Without a for-cause termination path, parties must rely on common-law material-breach doctrines, which are jurisdiction-dependent.","id":"TERM-002-s1-0","rule_id":"TERM-002","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"warning","source_citations":[],"title":"No termination-for-cause clause detected"},{"description":"The contract does not state what happens upon termination.","document_position":0,"excerpt":{"end_offset":0,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":0,"text":"(no effect-of-termination clause)"},"explanation":"An effect-of-termination clause spells out the rights and obligations that survive, the return or destruction of materials, and the wind-down rules.","id":"TERM-005-s1-0","rule_id":"TERM-005","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"warning","source_citations":[],"title":"No effect-of-termination clause detected"},{"description":"No reference to Table 3 / Appendix Information was found.","document_position":0,"excerpt":{"end_offset":0,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":0,"text":"(clause absent from the document)"},"explanation":"Table 3 incorporates the EU SCC Annex information into the UK Addendum.","id":"TRANSFER-013-s1-0","recommendation":"Complete Table 3 with the SCC Annex information (parties, transfer, supervisory authority, TOMs).","rule_id":"TRANSFER-013","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"warning","source_citations":[{"id":"transfer-ico-uk-addendum-mandatory-clauses-table-3","license":"Public domain or regulator re-use","license_url":"https://www.usa.gov/government-works","retrieved_at":"2026-05-12T00:00:00Z","source":"ICO UK Addendum Mandatory Clauses, Table 3","source_url":"https://ico.org.uk/for-organisations/uk-gdpr-guidance-and-resources/international-transfers/international-data-transfer-agreement-and-guidance/"}],"title":"UK Addendum Table 3 (Appendix Information) missing"},{"description":"No fallback clause was found in case the adequacy decision is invalidated.","document_position":0,"excerpt":{"end_offset":0,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":0,"text":"(clause absent from the document)"},"explanation":"Adequacy decisions can be invalidated (Schrems I, Schrems II). A fallback to SCCs / IDTA prevents transfer disruption.","id":"TRANSFER-018-s1-0","recommendation":"Add: 'In the event the relied-upon adequacy decision is invalidated, the parties shall promptly implement the EU SCCs / UK Addendum / UK IDTA as a fallback.'","rule_id":"TRANSFER-018","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"warning","source_citations":[{"id":"transfer-gdpr-art-45-adequacy-decisions","license":"Public domain or regulator re-use","license_url":"https://www.usa.gov/government-works","retrieved_at":"2026-05-12T00:00:00Z","source":"GDPR Art. 45 / Adequacy decisions","source_url":"https://commission.europa.eu/law/law-topic/data-protection/international-dimension-data-protection/adequacy-decisions_en"}],"title":"Adequacy fallback clause missing"},{"description":"No reference to onward-transfer terms (Clause 8.7 / 8.8) was found.","document_position":0,"excerpt":{"end_offset":0,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":0,"text":"(clause absent from the document)"},"explanation":"SCC Clause 8.7 / 8.8 governs onward transfers to third parties outside the EEA. For the UK Addendum (layered on EU SCCs), Clause 8.8 is incorporated by reference but explicit acknowledgment is best practice.","id":"TRANSFER-020-s1-0","recommendation":"Include the Clause 8.7 / 8.8 text or its substantive equivalent in the DPA.","rule_id":"TRANSFER-020","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"warning","source_citations":[{"id":"transfer-eu-sccs-clause-8-7-8-8","license":"Public domain or regulator re-use","license_url":"https://www.usa.gov/government-works","retrieved_at":"2026-05-12T00:00:00Z","source":"EU SCCs Clause 8.7 / 8.8","source_url":"https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/dec_impl/2021/914/oj"}],"title":"Onward-transfer terms missing"},{"description":"The document does not state where disputes must be brought.","document_position":0,"excerpt":{"end_offset":0,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":0,"text":"(no venue clause)"},"explanation":"Without a venue clause, default venue rules apply (in federal court, 28 U.S.C. § 1391). A clear forum-selection clause avoids ambiguity.","id":"CHOICE-003-s1-0","rule_id":"CHOICE-003","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"info","source_citations":[{"id":"stat-28-usc-1391","license":"Public domain (US government work)","license_url":"https://www.usa.gov/government-works","retrieved_at":"2026-05-11T00:00:00Z","source":"28 U.S.C. § 1391 (venue generally)","source_url":"https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/28/1391"}],"title":"No venue / forum clause detected"},{"description":"Vaulytica did not find a Definitions section or any inline-defined terms.","document_position":0,"excerpt":{"end_offset":0,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":0,"text":"(no definitions located)"},"explanation":"Most non-trivial contracts capitalize defined terms and either set them out in a Definitions section or define them inline (\"X\" means …). Their absence is not by itself a problem, but downstream rules that check for use of specific defined terms will be skipped.","id":"STRUCT-004-s1-0","rule_id":"STRUCT-004","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"info","source_citations":[],"title":"No defined terms detected"}],"playbook_id":"uk-idta-addendum","playbook_match_confidence":1,"playbook_match_reasoning":"forced via sidecar to uk-idta-addendum","result_hash":"134ae966aad8efc2dd70b1ebefd0bd53942aff911d5124bdbea49ad8968b56d5","source_file":{"name":"uk-idta-addendum-missing-table-3-fail.txt","sha256":"cb1bd95bd5a97f22e4d98df455765253a06380cea3002471c112d749f6432753","size_bytes":1},"version":"9.41.0"}